{"title_page": "South Hampstead High School", "text_new": "{{advert|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2014}}\n{{Infobox UK school\n | name                  = South Hampstead High School\n | image                 = South Hampstead High School logo crest.jpg\n | caption               = \n | image_size            = 150px\n | coordinates           = {{coord|51.5462|-0.1773|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dec|display=inline,title}}\n | motto                 = More Light <br>({{lang-de|Mehr Licht}})\n | established           = 1876\n | closed                = \n | type                  = [[Independent school (United Kingdom)|Independent]] day school\n | religious_affiliation = \n | president             = \n | head_label            = \n | head                  = Victoria Bingham\n | founder               = \n | specialist            = \n | address               = 3 Maresfield Gardens\n | city                  = [[South Hampstead]]\n | county                = [[Greater London]]\n | country               = England\n | postcode              = NW3 5SS\n | local_authority       = [[London Borough of Camden]]\n | ofsted                = yes\n | urn                   = 100076\n | staff                 = circa 160\n | enrolment             = 930\n | gender                = Girls\n | lower_age             = 4\n | upper_age             = 18\n | houses                = Walker, Potter, Bodington, Benton\n | colours               = [[Gold (colour)|Gold]] and [[Navy (color)|Navy]] {{color box|#FFFF00}} {{color box|#000080}}\n | publication           = The Penguin (student magazine)\n | free_label_1          = \n | free_1                = \n | free_label_2          = \n | free_2                = \n | free_label_3          = \n | free_3                = \n | website               = {{url|www.shhs.gdst.net}}\n}}\n\n'''South Hampstead High School''' is an [[Independent school (United Kingdom)|independent day school]] in [[Hampstead]], north-west [[London]], England, which was founded by the [[Girls' Day School Trust]] (GDST). It is for girls aged 4\u201318 with selective entry at ages 4+, 7+, 11+ and 16+ (Sixth Form). \n\n==History==\nThe school was founded in 1876, the ninth school established by the GDST (previously known at the Girls' Public Day School Trust), as the St John's Wood School, with 27 pupils. In 1887, it changed its name to South Hampstead High School. From 1946 until the late 1970s, it was a girls' [[direct grant grammar school]], with around half the intake paid for by the local council.<ref>{{cite web|author=Mr. K. Lindsay |url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/written_answers/1946/may/31/grammar-schools-direct-grant-status |title=Direct grant status |publisher=Hansard.millbanksystems.com |date=31 May 1946 |accessdate=26 January 2011 }}</ref> In January 2015, alumna Helena Bonham Carter officially opened a new 7-storey building for the Senior School, designed by [[Hopkins Architects]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hamhigh.co.uk/education/actress-helena-bonham-carter-opens-hampstead-school-new-building-1-3937757|title=Belsize Park actress Helena Bonham Carter reminisces about Hampstead schooldays|last=Blake|first=Imogen|website=Hampstead Highgate Express|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> In January 2020, the school unveiled a new state-of-the-art performance space, Waterlow Hall. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hamhigh.co.uk/education/helena-bonham-carter-and-olivia-colman-open-south-hampstead-school-hall-1-6489197|title=Royal guests: Crown stars Helena Bonham Carter and Olivia Colman open South Hampstead school\u2019s arts hall|last=Boniface|first=Michael|website=Hampstead Highgate Express|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n==Staff==\n\n===Head Teachers===\n* Victoria Bingham 2017\u2013 present\n* Sandrine Paillasse 2016 (acting)\n* Helen Pike 2013\u20132016\n* Elizabeth Nicholas 2013, one term\n* Jenny Stephen 2005\u20132013\n* Vivien Ainley 2001\u20132004\n* Jean Scott 1993\u20132001 (Chairman from 2001\u20136 of the [[Independent Schools Council]], and also Head from 1986\u201393 of [[St. George's School, Edinburgh]])\n* Averil Burgess OBE 1975\u201393 (President from 1988\u20139 of the [[Girls' Schools Association]])\n* Sheila Wiltshire 1969\u20131974\n* Prunella Bodington 1954\u20131969\n* Muriel Potter 1927\u20131954  \n* Dorothy Walker 1918\u20131926 (Miss McGonigle 1926 one term) \n* Mary Benton 1886\u20131918\n* Rita Allen-Olney 1876\u20131886\n\n===Former teachers===\n* Edith Allen, mother of food writer [[Raymond Postgate]] and Dame [[Margaret Cole]] (who married [[G. D. H. Cole]]), and wife of classicist [[John Percival Postgate]]\n* [[Rosalind Goodfellow]], who taught history<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/rosalind-goodfellow-first-woman-moderator-of-the-general-assembly-of-the-united-reformed-church-964175.html Rosalind Goodfellow]</ref>\n* Marianne Lutz, Headmistress from 1959\u201383 of [[Sheffield High School (South Yorkshire)|Sheffield High School for Girls]] taught history from 1947\u201359.\n* [[Margaret Nevinson]], suffragette, and mother of the painter [[Christopher R. W. Nevinson]] (taught classics in the 1880s)\n* Marie Orliac, who taught French in 1907-1910, founder of the University des Lettres Francaises (1910, Marble Arch, West London) that would become in 1913 the [[Institut_francais_du_Royaume-Uni|Institut Francais du Royaume-Uni]].\n\n==Academic results==\nIn 2019, South Hampstead High School was ranked 13th in the country for A Level results, based on data collated by the [[Independent Schools Council]] (ISC).\n\nTypically around one fifth of the student body goes on to study at the universities of [[Oxford]] and [[Cambridge]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shhs.gdst.net/sixth-form/leavers-destinations/|title=Leavers\u2019 destinations|website=South Hampstead High School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n==School motto==\n* \"Mehr Licht\" \u2013 More Light (German)\u2014the reputed last words of [[Johann Wolfgang von Goethe]]\n\n==Notable former pupils==\n{{Alumni|date=November 2014| To avoid removal of names, references to independent reliable sources are needed, these that show listed former pupils attended this school}}\n{{see also|Category:People educated at South Hampstead High School}}\n*[[Katya Adler|Katya Adler,]] journalist \n*[[Naomi Alderman]], author\n* [[Madalyn Aslan]], author\n* [[Alma Birk|Alma Birk, Baroness Birk]], Labour politician\n* [[Helena Bonham Carter]], actress\n* Prof [[Julia Briggs]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Julia Briggs \u2013 obituaries|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/opinion/obituaries/article2080102.ece|accessdate=5 June 2014|publisher=The Times|date=3 September 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Irene Bruegel]]<ref>{{cite news | first1= Sue |last1=Himmelweit | first2 = Simon | last2 =Mohun | author-link1=Susan Himmelweit |url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2008/oct/15/women-highereducation |title=Obituary: Irene Bruegel  |publisher=The Guardian |date= 15 October 2008 |accessdate=26 January 2011 |location=London}}</ref>\n* [[Ann Chegwidden]], film editor<ref>{{cite news|author=Michael Ratcliffe |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2007/oct/23/guardianobituaries.obituaries1 |title=Obituary: Ann Chegwidden |publisher=The Guardian |date= 23 October 2007 |accessdate=26 January 2011 |location=London}}</ref>\n* [[Janet Neel Cohen, Baroness Cohen of Pimlico]], author and former BBC governor\n* [[Joyti De-Laurey]], Britain's biggest female fraudster (and moreover, the daughter of the victim was herself an SHJS pupil).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/home/you/article-548068/Britains-Biggest-Female-Fraudster-Admits-It-fun-lasted.html |title=Britain's Biggest Female Fraudster Admits: 'It was fun while it lasted' &#124; Mail Online |publisher=Dailymail.co.uk |date=30 March 2008 |accessdate=26 January 2011 |location=London |first=Louette |last=Harding}}</ref>\n* [[Lynsey de Paul]], singer/songwriter/pianist/actress\n* [[Una Ellis-Fermor]], [[Sir Hildred Carlile, 1st Baronet|Hildred Carlile]] Professor of English from 1947\u201358 at Bedford College\n* [[Lynne Featherstone]], Liberal Democrat MP from 2005 to 2015 for [[Hornsey and Wood Green (UK Parliament constituency)|Hornsey and Wood Green]]\n* Dame [[Gwen Ffrangcon-Davies]], actress\n* [[Antonia Forest]] (Patricia Rubinstein), British children's author\n* [[Jill Fraser]], theatre director\n* [[Jane Green (author)|Jane Green]], author\n* [[Vivien Greene]] (''n\u00e9e'' Dayrell-Browning), wife of author [[Graham Greene]]\n* [[Wendy Greengross]](1925\u20132012), general practitioner and broadcaster<ref name=\"ONDB\">{{cite web|last1=Bayfield |first1=Tony |title=Greengross [married name Katz, later Kates], Wendy Elsa (1925\u20132012) |url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/106704 |website=ONDB |publisher=OUP |accessdate=26 November 2017}}</ref> \n* [[Charlotte Haldane]] (n\u00e9e Franken), writer, and first wife of evolutionary biologist [[J. B. S. Haldane]] from 1926\u201345\n* [[Amanda Harlech]], model <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/fashion/stellamagazine/3363816/Amanda-Harlech-a-charmed-life.html |title=Amanda Harlech: a charmed life |publisher=Telegraph |date=2 December 2007 |accessdate= 14 November 2010 |location=London |first=Justine |last=Picardie}}</ref>\n* [[Margot Heinemann]], left-wing writer\n* [[Elizabeth Irving]] (Lady Brunner), actress and founder of the [[Keep Britain Tidy]] Campaign\n* [[Elsie Janner]], Baroness Janner CBE, wife of [[Barnett Janner, Baron Janner]]\n* [[Laura Janner-Klausner]], their daughter; Senior Rabbi, [[Movement for Reform Judaism]] \n* [[Miriam Karlin]], actress and activist\n* [[Suzy Klein]], radio and television presenter, writer and producer\n* [[Angela Lansbury]], actress\n* [[Una Ledingham]] (n\u00e9e Garvin),<ref>{{cite journal|pmc=1846661 |title=Una Ledingham |date= | page=1314 |volume=2 |issue=5473 |journal=British Medical Journal}}</ref> physician in the field of [[diabetes mellitus and pregnancy]], and daughter of [[James Louis Garvin]]\n* Nora Lee (n\u00e9e [[Nora Francisca Blackburne]]), actress and casting director <ref>The way we were: my life in pictures, The Times 23 August 2005</ref>\n* [[E. C. R. Lorac]], crime writer\n* [[Daisy Lowe]], model\n* [[Ruth Mace]], Professor of Evolutionary Anthropology since 2004 at [[University College London]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/anthropology/staff/r_mace |title=Ruth Mace |publisher=Ucl.ac.uk |date= |accessdate=26 January 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Joanna MacGregor]], pianist\n* [[Shirley Manson]], rock musician \n* [[Lucasta Miller]], writer\n* [[Kate Moross]], graphic designer\n* [[Sophie Newton]], entrepreneur \n* [[Julia Neuberger]], Rabbi\n* [[Freya North]], author\n* [[Margaret Quass]], educationalist\n* [[Dinah Rajak]], anthropologist, Susses University, daughter of Tessa Goldsmith\n* [[Tessa Rajak]] (n\u00e9e Goldsmith), Professor Emerita of Ancient History, Reading University \n* [[Netta Rheinberg]] MBE, cricketer\n* Diana Rowntree, architecture journalist<ref>{{cite news|author=Fiona MacCarthy |url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2008/aug/27/architecture.pressandpublishing |title=Obituary: Diana Rowntree &#124; Art and design |publisher=The Guardian |date= 27 August 2008 |accessdate=26 January 2011 |location=London}}</ref>\n* [[Jordan Scott]], photographer, daughter of [[Ridley Scott]]\n* [[Georgia Slowe]], actress\n* [[Anna Stothard]] (briefly), author\n* [[Rachel Sylvester]], columnist at ''[[The Times]]'' \n* [[Flora Twort]], English painter\n* [[Jess Wade]], physicist\n* [[Fay Weldon]], author\n* [[Olivia Williams]], actress\n* [[Sula Wolff]], child psychiatrist\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of direct grant grammar schools]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}<!--added above External links/Sources by script-assisted edit-->\n\n==External links==\n{{official website|http://www.shhs.gdst.net/}}\n[[Category:Independent girls' schools in London]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1876]]\n[[Category:Schools of the Girls' Day School Trust]]\n[[Category:Independent schools in the London Borough of Camden]]\n[[Category:1876 establishments in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{advert|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2014}}\n{{Infobox UK school\n | name                    = South Hampstead High School\n | image                   = [[File:South Hampstead High School logo crest.jpg|thumb|South Hampstead High School crest]]\n | image_size              = 150px\n | coordinates             = {{coord|51.5462|-0.1773|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dec|display=inline,title}}\n | motto                   = More Light <br>({{lang-de|Mehr Licht}})\n | established             = 1876\n | closed                  = \n | type                    = [[Independent school (United Kingdom)|Independent]] day school\n | religious_affiliation   = \n | president               = \n | head_label              = \n | head                    = Victoria Bingham\n | founder                 = \n | specialist              = \n | address                 = 3 Maresfield Gardens\n | city                    = [[South Hampstead]]\n | county                  = [[Greater London]]\n | country                 = England\n | postcode                = NW3 5SS\n | local_authority         = [[London Borough of Camden]]\n | ofsted                  = yes\n | urn                     = 100076\n | staff                   = circa 160\n | enrolment               = 930\n | gender                  = Girls\n | lower_age               = 4\n | upper_age               = 18\n | houses                  = Walker, Potter, Bodington, Benton\n | colours                 = [[Gold (colour)|Gold]] and [[Navy (color)|Navy]] {{color box|#FFFF00}} {{color box|#000080}}\n | publication             = The Penguin (student magazine)\n | free_label_1            = \n | free_1                  = \n | free_label_2            = \n | free_2                  = \n | free_label_3            = \n | free_3                  = \n | website                 = http://www.shhs.gdst.net/\n}}\n\n'''South Hampstead High School''' is an [[Independent school (United Kingdom)|independent day school]] in [[Hampstead]], north-west [[London]], England, which was founded by the [[Girls' Day School Trust]] (GDST). It is for girls aged 4\u201318 with selective entry at ages 4+, 7+, 11+ and 16+ (Sixth Form). \n\n==History==\nThe school was founded in 1876, the ninth school established by the GDST (previously known at the Girls' Public Day School Trust), as the St John's Wood School, with 27 pupils. In 1887, it changed its name to South Hampstead High School. From 1946 until the late 1970s, it was a girls' [[direct grant grammar school]], with around half the intake paid for by the local council.<ref>{{cite web|author=Mr. K. Lindsay |url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/written_answers/1946/may/31/grammar-schools-direct-grant-status |title=Direct grant status |publisher=Hansard.millbanksystems.com |date=31 May 1946 |accessdate=26 January 2011 }}</ref> In January 2015, alumna Helena Bonham Carter officially opened a new 7-storey building for the Senior School, designed by [[Hopkins Architects]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hamhigh.co.uk/education/actress-helena-bonham-carter-opens-hampstead-school-new-building-1-3937757|title=Belsize Park actress Helena Bonham Carter reminisces about Hampstead schooldays|last=Blake|first=Imogen|website=Hampstead Highgate Express|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> In January 2020, the school unveiled a new state-of-the-art performance space, Waterlow Hall. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hamhigh.co.uk/education/helena-bonham-carter-and-olivia-colman-open-south-hampstead-school-hall-1-6489197|title=Royal guests: Crown stars Helena Bonham Carter and Olivia Colman open South Hampstead school\u2019s arts hall|last=Boniface|first=Michael|website=Hampstead Highgate Express|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n==Staff==\n\n===Head Teachers===\n* Victoria Bingham 2017\u2013 present\n* Sandrine Paillasse 2016 (acting)\n* Helen Pike 2013\u20132016\n* Elizabeth Nicholas 2013, one term\n* Jenny Stephen 2005\u20132013\n* Vivien Ainley 2001\u20132004\n* Jean Scott 1993\u20132001 (Chairman from 2001\u20136 of the [[Independent Schools Council]], and also Head from 1986\u201393 of [[St. George's School, Edinburgh]])\n* Averil Burgess OBE 1975\u201393 (President from 1988\u20139 of the [[Girls' Schools Association]])\n* Sheila Wiltshire 1969\u20131974\n* Prunella Bodington 1954\u20131969\n* Muriel Potter 1927\u20131954  \n* Dorothy Walker 1918\u20131926 (Miss McGonigle 1926 one term) \n* Mary Benton 1886\u20131918\n* Rita Allen-Olney 1876\u20131886\n\n===Former teachers===\n* Edith Allen, mother of food writer [[Raymond Postgate]] and Dame [[Margaret Cole]] (who married [[G. D. H. Cole]]), and wife of classicist [[John Percival Postgate]]\n* [[Rosalind Goodfellow]], who taught history<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/rosalind-goodfellow-first-woman-moderator-of-the-general-assembly-of-the-united-reformed-church-964175.html Rosalind Goodfellow]</ref>\n* Marianne Lutz, Headmistress from 1959\u201383 of [[Sheffield High School (South Yorkshire)|Sheffield High School for Girls]] taught history from 1947\u201359.\n* [[Margaret Nevinson]], suffragette, and mother of the painter [[Christopher R. W. Nevinson]] (taught classics in the 1880s)\n* Marie Orliac, who taught French in 1907-1910, founder of the University des Lettres Francaises (1910, Marble Arch, West London) that would become in 1913 the [[Institut_francais_du_Royaume-Uni|Institut Francais du Royaume-Uni]].\n\n==Academic results==\nIn 2019, South Hampstead High School was ranked 13th in the country for A Level results, based on data collated by the [[Independent Schools Council]] (ISC).\n\nTypically around one fifth of the student body goes on to study at the universities of [[Oxford]] and [[Cambridge]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shhs.gdst.net/sixth-form/leavers-destinations/|title=Leavers\u2019 destinations|website=South Hampstead High School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n==School motto==\n* \"Mehr Licht\" \u2013 More Light (German)\u2014the reputed last words of [[Johann Wolfgang von Goethe]]\n\n==Notable former pupils==\n{{Alumni|date=November 2014| To avoid removal of names, references to independent reliable sources are needed, these that show listed former pupils attended this school}}\n{{see also|Category:People educated at South Hampstead High School}}\n*[[Katya Adler|Katya Adler,]] journalist \n*[[Naomi Alderman]], author\n* [[Madalyn Aslan]], author\n* [[Alma Birk|Alma Birk, Baroness Birk]], Labour politician\n* [[Helena Bonham Carter]], actress\n* Prof [[Julia Briggs]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Julia Briggs \u2013 obituaries|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/opinion/obituaries/article2080102.ece|accessdate=5 June 2014|publisher=The Times|date=3 September 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Irene Bruegel]]<ref>{{cite news | first1= Sue |last1=Himmelweit | first2 = Simon | last2 =Mohun | author-link1=Susan Himmelweit |url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2008/oct/15/women-highereducation |title=Obituary: Irene Bruegel  |publisher=The Guardian |date= 15 October 2008 |accessdate=26 January 2011 |location=London}}</ref>\n* [[Ann Chegwidden]], film editor<ref>{{cite news|author=Michael Ratcliffe |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2007/oct/23/guardianobituaries.obituaries1 |title=Obituary: Ann Chegwidden |publisher=The Guardian |date= 23 October 2007 |accessdate=26 January 2011 |location=London}}</ref>\n* [[Janet Neel Cohen, Baroness Cohen of Pimlico]], author and former BBC governor\n* [[Joyti De-Laurey]], Britain's biggest female fraudster (and moreover, the daughter of the victim was herself an SHJS pupil).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/home/you/article-548068/Britain