, actress\n* [[Sula Wolff]], child psychiatrist\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of direct grant grammar schools]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}<!--added above External links/Sources by script-assisted edit-->\n\n==External links==\n{{official website|http://www.shhs.gdst.net/}}\n[[Category:Independent girls' schools in London]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1876]]\n[[Category:Schools of the Girls' Day School Trust]]\n[[Category:Independent schools in the London Borough of Camden]]\n[[Category:1876 establishments in England]]\n", "name_user": "MB", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix infobox image syntax", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/South_Hampstead_High_School"}
{"title_page": "Lake of Tears", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=August 2007}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Lake of Tears\n| image               = AX Lake of Tears ProRock-01.jpg\n| caption             = Lake of Tears at ProRock 2009 in Ukraine.<br>From left to right: Fredrik Jordanius, Mikael Larsson, Johan Oudhuis and Daniel Brennare.\n| image_size          =\n| landscape           = yes\n| background          = group_or_band \n| origin              = [[Bor\u00e5s]], Sweden\n| instrument          = \n| genre               = [[Gothic metal]] <br> [[Doom metal]] <br> [[Progressive metal]] <br> [[Gothic rock]]\n| years_active        = 1994\u20132000, 2003\u2013present \n| label               = [[Black Mark Production|Black Mark]], [[Noise Records (Germany)|Noise]], [[Dockyard1]]\n| website             = [http://www.lakeoftears.net lakeoftears.net]\n| current_members     = [[Daniel Brennare]]<br />[[Mikael Larsson]]<br />[[Johan Oudhuis]]<br /> [[Fredrik Jordanius]]\n| past_members        = [[Jonas Eriksson (rhythm guitarist)|Jonas Eriksson]]<br/>[[Christian Saarinen]]<br/>[[Ulrik Lindblom]]<br />[[Magnus Sahlgren]]\n}}\n\n'''Lake of Tears''' is a Swedish [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] band originally formed in 1994, generally considered to play [[gothic metal]]/[[gothic rock]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.queensofsteel.com/2005/03/lake-of-teras-eng/ |title=Lake Of Tears (Eng.) |website=Queensofsteel.com |date=2011-04-28 |accessdate=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metalreviews.com/reviews/album/3907 |title=Lake of Tears - Moons and Mushrooms |website=Metalreviews.com |date=2007-07-13 |accessdate=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref>[https://www.metalblast.net/music-review/lake-of-tears-by-the-black-sea/] {{dead link|date=March 2020}}</ref> and [[doom metal]]. However, their sound has expanded to include [[psychedelic rock]] and [[progressive rock]] elements. The band broke up in 2000 amid creative differences, but reunited in late 2003, releasing the acclaimed album ''[[Black Brick Road]]''. They released their eighth studio album, ''[[Illwill (album)|Illwill]]'', in April 2011. In 2014 they released their first live album, ''[[By the Black Sea (album)|By the Black Sea]]''.\n\n== History ==\n===Early years===\nLake of Tears was founded in the early 1990s by Daniel Brennare, Jonas Eriksson, [[Mikael Larsson]] and [[Johan Oudhuis]].  Their first album, entitled ''[[Greater Art]]'', was released through the record label [[Black Mark Production]] in 1994. The album is [[doom metal]] featuring coarse, ragged vocals and crushing guitars. The band would subsequently steer away from such a directly categorized style, only revisiting it on their 2011 release ''[[Illwill (album)|Illwill]]''.\n\nLake of Tears wowed critics and fans alike with their second recording, ''[[Headstones (album)|Headstones]]'', released in 1995. The music underwent important changes, expanding on the riff-base of [[doom metal]] to achieve a more melodic and melancholic sound. The lyrics also explored new territory, intensely mournful and psychedelic fantasy imagery enhancing the album's heavy, autumnal soundscapes.\n\n[[Image:AX Lake of Tears ProRock-02.jpg|thumb|right|Lake of Tears during ProRock-2009 festival<br />LTR: Fredrik Jordanius, Johan Oudhuis, Daniel Brennare]]\n[[Image:AX Lake of Tears ProRock-03.jpg|thumb|right|Lake of Tears during ProRock-2009 festival<br />LTR: Mikael Larsson, Johan Oudhuis, Daniel Brennare]]\n[[Image:Brennare LoT ProRock.jpg|thumb|right|Daniel Brennare at ProRock 2009 festival]]\n[[Image:Larsson LoT ProRock.jpg|thumb|right|Mikael Larsson at ProRock 2009 festival]]\n\n===Mid-career success: A Crimson Cosmos===\n1997 brought the release of the band's most popular studio effort until then, ''[[A Crimson Cosmos]]''.  If ''[[Headstones (album)|Headstones]]'' had been a revision of their earlier sound, ''A Crimson Cosmos'' was a complete rebirth, being a hypnotically melodic album.  The release's closing track, \"[[A Crimson Cosmos (song)|A Crimson Cosmos]]\", reflected a marked influence by [[Progressive rock|progressive]]/[[psychedelic rock|psychedelic]] luminaries [[Pink Floyd]], while other tracks, such as [[Lady Rosenred]] and [[Raistlin and the Rose]] reflected popular fantasy themes.  Rhythm guitarist Jonas Eriksson had left the band before the release, being replaced by guitarist [[Ulrik Lindblom]]. After recording ''A Crimson Cosmos'' and touring with Lake of Tears until 1999, he also left the band and had to be substituted by [[Magnus Sahlgren]], who played as lead guitarist, but only as a guest artist. Although he played on ''[[Forever Autumn (album)|Forever Autumn]]'' and every subsequent Lake of Tears album, often composing the majority of lead guitar riffs, Sahlgren was only formally accepted as a band member following the release of 2004's ''[[Black Brick Road]]''.\n\nLake of Tears' 1999 album, ''[[Forever Autumn (album)|Forever Autumn]]'', did not follow the trend settled by ''Headstones'' and ''A Crimson Cosmos'', resulting an intensely quiet and introspective album. Keyboardist [[Christian Saarinen]] was briefly included as an official band member, adding an extra layer to the band's sound. Fantasy imagery was rife and the album's overall effect was sedate and sorrowful.\n\n===The breakup===\nBecause of personal and creative differences, but also (and perhaps more-so) because of the lack of attention the band received from their label, the band went their separate ways shortly after the release of ''Forever Autumn'', though they were still contractually bound to deliver one more album for [[Black Mark Production]]. This being the case, Brennare and Sahlgren retreated to the studio to record ''[[The Neonai]]'', an [[electronica]]-influenced album relying on drum machines and uncharacteristically slick production values. The resulting album was released in 2002, and featured some of the band's most inspired songwriting and memorable melodies, regardless of the hasty manner in which it was composed and recorded.\n\n===The reunion and recent activity===\nIn 2003 the band reunited out of boredom, participating in several jams.  They were quick to realize that the brief hiatus had reinvigorated their collective spirits, and began to tentatively compose the material eventually released on their 2004 endeavor, ''[[Black Brick Road]]''.  Feeling that [[Black Mark Production]] had failed to market them appropriately, Lake of Tears began shopping for a new record label, and eventually settled on [[Noise Records (Germany)|Noise Records]].  The subsequent release of ''Black Brick Road'' found the band exploring fresh concepts -the majority of the songs are highly abstract in nature, focusing on emotional states and dream- like imagery over specific nods to fantasy fiction and narrative structure.  Following the album's release, [[Magnus Sahlgren]] was finally accepted as a member of the band, making his almost five years association official.\n\nLake of Tears released their 7th studio album ''[[Moons and Mushrooms]]'' on April 26, 2007. The album featured a heavier approach to the guitar-work, unlike ''Black Brick Road'' whose melodies were primarily conceived via keyboard experimentation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalfan.ro/articol.php?sectiune=2&id_doc=1898&lng=2 |title=LAKE OF TEARS: ... of moons and mushrooms |language=ro |website=Metalfan.ro |date=2007-08-08 |accessdate=2020-03-23}}</ref> The music was created directly in the rehearsal room, a new approach for the band. [[Moons and Mushrooms]] has a harder rock sound, though Brennare's lyrics continued to lean towards the melancholic and conceptual. \n\nA new album titled ''[[Illwill (album)|Illwill]]'' was released on April 29, 2011. It features an even heavier, darker approach, eschewing the band's typical evocation of mournful themes in favor of bleak and disturbing imagery.\n\nLake of Tears released their first-ever live album on January 31, 2014. The album is titled \"By the Black Sea,\" and includes a full concert with 16 songs recorded earlier this year in Bucharest, Romania. It is also available as DVD/CD set.<ref>[http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/lake-of-tears-to-release-live-album/] {{dead link|date=March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Current line-up ==\n* [[Daniel Brennare]] - Vocals/Guitar (1994\u2013present)\n* [[Mikael Larsson]] - Bass (1994\u2013present)\n* [[Johan Oudhuis]] - Drums (1994\u2013present)\n* [[Fredrik Jordanius]] - Lead guitar (2009\u2013present)\n\n=== Former members ===\n* [[Jonas Eriksson (rhythm guitarist)|Jonas Eriksson]] - Rhythm guitar (1994\u20131997)\n* [[Christian Saarinen]] - Keyboards (1999\u20132000)\n* [[Ulrik Lindblom]] - Guitar (1997\u20131999)\n* [[Magnus Sahlgren]] - Lead guitar (as a guest artist: 1999 / officially: 2004 - 2009)\n\n==Discography==\n===Full length===\n*''[[Greater Art]]'' (1994)\n*''[[Headstones (album)|Headstones]]'' (1995)\n*''[[A Crimson Cosmos]]'' (1997)\n*''[[Forever Autumn (album)|Forever Autumn]]'' (1999)\n*''[[The Neonai]]'' (2002)\n*''[[Black Brick Road]]'' (2004)\n*''[[Moons and Mushrooms]]'' (2007)\n*''[[Illwill (album)|Illwill]]'' (2011)\n\n=== Compilations and singles ===\n*''[[Lady Rosenred]]'' (1997)\n*''[[Sorcerers (album)|Sorcerers]]'' (2002)\n*''[[Greatest Tears Vol. I]]'' (2004)\n*''[[Greatest Tears Vol. II]]'' (2004)\n\n===Live albums===\n*''By the Black Sea'' (2014)\n\n==Sources==\n*[http://www.dockyard1.com Dockyard 1, label]\n*[http://www.dragon-productions.com Dragon Productions, booking agency]\n*[http://www.studiomega.se Home for the BBR recording]\n*[http://www.noiserecords.com Noise Records, old label]\n*[http://www.blackmark.net Black Mark, old label]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.lakeoftears.net Official band web site]\n*[http://www.lakeoftears.org Official fan web site]\n*[http://www.myspace.com/thelakeoftears Lake of Tears on MySpace]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140203125101/http://www.waterytimes.com/index.php?no=8&location=N008C03&txt=N008C03T00 Europe\u2019s Times and Unknown Waters, Ormeny, Francisc-Norbert (30 December 2012).\"The Secrets of the Swedish New Moon\". ]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140203125059/http://www.waterytimes.com/index.php?no=8&location=N008C03&txt=N008C03T01 Europe\u2019s Times and Unknown Waters, Ormeny, Theodora-Eva (30 December 2012).  \"The Aesthetics of Evil Part I\". ]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140203125103/http://www.waterytimes.com/index.php?no=8&location=N008C03&txt=N008C03T02 Europe\u2019s Times and Unknown Waters, Ormeny, Theodora-Eva (30 December 2012).  \"The Aesthetics of Evil Part II\". ]\n\n{{Lake of Tears}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lake Of Tears}}\n[[Category:Swedish heavy metal musical groups]]\n[[Category:Swedish doom metal musical groups]]\n[[Category:Swedish gothic metal musical groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1994]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 2000]]\n[[Category:Musical groups reestablished in 2003]]\n[[Category:Musical quartets]]\n[[Category:1994 establishments in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Black Mark Production artists]]\n[[Category:Noise Records artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=August 2007}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Lake of Tears\n| image               = AX Lake of Tears ProRock-01.jpg\n| caption             = Lake of Tears at ProRock 2009 in Ukraine.<br>From left to right: Fredrik Jordanius, Mikael Larsson, Johan Oudhuis and Daniel Brennare.\n| image_size          =\n| landscape           = yes\n| background          = group_or_band \n| origin              = [[Bor\u00e5s]], Sweden\n| instrument          = \n| genre               = [[Gothic metal]] <br> [[Doom metal]] <br> [[Progressive metal]] <br> [[Gothic rock]]\n| years_active        = 1994\u20132000, 2003\u2013present \n| label               = [[Black Mark Production|Black Mark]], [[Noise Records (Germany)|Noise]], [[Dockyard1]]\n| website             = [http://www.lakeoftears.net lakeoftears.net]\n| current_members     = [[Daniel Brennare]]<br />[[Mikael Larsson]]<br />[[Johan Oudhuis]]<br /> [[Fredrik Jordanius]]\n| past_members        = [[Jonas Eriksson (rhythm guitarist)|Jonas Eriksson]]<br/>[[Christian Saarinen]]<br/>[[Ulrik Lindblom]]<br />[[Magnus Sahlgren]]\n}}\n\n'''Lake of Tears''' is a Swedish [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] band originally formed in 1994, generally considered to play [[gothic metal]]/[[gothic rock]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.queensofsteel.com/2005/03/lake-of-teras-eng/ |title=Lake Of Tears (Eng.) |website=Queensofsteel.com |date=2011-04-28 |accessdate=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metalreviews.com/reviews/album/3907 |title=Lake of Tears - Moons and Mushrooms |website=Metalreviews.com |date=2007-07-13 |accessdate=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref>[https://www.metalblast.net/music-review/lake-of-tears-by-the-black-sea/] {{dead link|date=March 2020}}</ref> and [[doom metal]]. However, their sound has expanded to include [[psychedelic rock]] and [[progressive rock]] elements. The band broke up in 2000 amid creative differences, but reunited in late 2003, releasing the acclaimed album ''[[Black Brick Road]]''. They released their eighth studio album, ''[[Illwill (album)|Illwill]]'', in April 2011. In 2014 they released their first live album, ''[[By the Black Sea (album)|By the Black Sea]]''.\n\n== History ==\n===Early years===\nLake of Tears was founded in the early 1990s by Daniel Brennare, Jonas Eriksson, [[Mikael Larsson]] and [[Johan Oudhuis]].  Their first album, entitled ''[[Greater Art]]'', was released through the record label [[Black Mark Production]] in 1994. The album is [[doom metal]] featuring coarse, ragged vocals and crushing guitars. The band would subsequently steer away from such a directly categorized style, only revisiting it on their 2011 release ''[[Illwill (album)|Illwill]]''.\n\nLake of Tears wowed critics and fans alike with their second recording, ''[[Headstones (album)|Headstones]]'', released in 1995. The music underwent important changes, expanding on the riff-base of [[doom metal]] to achieve a more melodic and melancholic sound. The lyrics also explored new territory, intensely mournful and psychedelic fantasy imagery enhancing the album's heavy, autumnal soundscapes.\n\n[[Image:AX Lake of Tears ProRock-02.jpg|thumb|right|Lake of Tears during ProRock-2009 festival<br />LTR: Fredrik Jordanius, Johan Oudhuis, Daniel Brennare]]\n[[Image:AX Lake of Tears ProRock-03.jpg|thumb|right|Lake of Tears during ProRock-2009 festival<br />LTR: Mikael Larsson, Johan Oudhuis, Daniel Brennare]]\n[[Image:Brennare LoT ProRock.jpg|thumb|right|Daniel Brennare at ProRock 2009 festival]]\n[[Image:Larsson LoT ProRock.jpg|thumb|right|Mikael Larsson at ProRock 2009 festival]]\n\n===Mid-career success: A Crimson Cosmos===\n1997 brought the release of the band's most popular studio effort until then, ''[[A Crimson Cosmos]]''.  If ''[[Headstones (album)|Headstones]]'' had been a revision of their earlier sound, ''A Crimson Cosmos'' was a complete rebirth, being a hypnotically melodic album.  The release's closing track, \"[[A Crimson Cosmos (song)|A Crimson Cosmos]]\", reflected a marked influence by [[Progressive rock|progressive]]/[[psychedelic rock|psychedelic]] luminaries [[Pink Floyd]], while other tracks, such as [[Lady Rosenred]] and [[Raistlin and the Rose]] reflected popular fantasy themes.  Rhythm guitarist Jonas Eriksson had left the band before the release, being replaced by guitarist [[Ulrik Lindblom]]. After recording ''A Crimson Cosmos'' and touring with Lake of Tears until 1999, he also left the band and had to be substituted by [[Magnus Sahlgren]], who played as lead guitarist, but only as a guest artist. Although he played on ''[[Forever Autumn (album)|Forever Autumn]]'' and every subsequent Lake of Tears album, often composing the majority of lead guitar riffs, Sahlgren was only formally accepted as a band member following the release of 2004's ''[[Black Brick Road]]''.\n\nLake of Tears' 1999 album, ''[[Forever Autumn (album)|Forever Autumn]]'', did not follow the trend settled by ''Headstones'' and ''A Crimson Cosmos'', resulting an intensely quiet and introspective album. Keyboardist [[Christian Saarinen]] was briefly included as an official band member, adding an extra layer to the band's sound. Fantasy imagery was rife and the album's overall effect was sedate and sorrowful.\n\n===The breakup===\nBecause of personal and creative differences, but also (and perhaps more-so) because of the lack of attention the band received from their label, the band went their separate ways shortly after the release of ''Forever Autumn'', though they were still contractually bound to deliver one more album for [[Black Mark Production]]. This being the case, Brennare and Sahlgren retreated to the studio to record ''[[The Neonai]]'', an [[electronica]]-influenced album relying on drum machines and uncharacteristically slick production values. The resulting album was released in 2002, and featured some of the band's most inspired songwriting and memorable melodies, regardless of the hasty manner in which it was composed and recorded.\n\n===The reunion and recent activity===\nIn 2003 the band reunited out of boredom, participating in several jams.  They were quick to realize that the brief hiatus had reinvigorated their collective spirits, and began to tentatively compose the material eventually released on their 2004 endeavor, ''[[Black Brick Road]]''.  Feeling that [[Black Mark Production]] had failed to market them appropriately, Lake of Tears began shopping for a new record label, and eventually settled on [[Noise Records (Germany)|Noise Records]].  The subsequent release of ''Black Brick Road'' found the band exploring fresh concepts -the majority of the songs are highly abstract in nature, focusing on emotional states and dream- like imagery over specific nods to fantasy fiction and narrative structure.  Following the album's release, [[Magnus Sahlgren]] was finally accepted as a member of the band, making his almost five years association official.\n\nLake of Tears released their 7th studio album ''[[Moons and Mushrooms]]'' on April 26, 2007. The album featured a heavier approach to the guitar-work, unlike ''Black Brick Road'' whose melodies were primarily conceived via keyboard experimentation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalfan.ro/articol.php?sectiune=2&id_doc=1898&lng=2 |title=LAKE OF TEARS: ... of moons and mushrooms |language={{in lang|ro}} |website=Metalfan.ro |date=2007-08-08 |accessdate=2020-03-23}}</ref> The music was created directly in the rehearsal room, a new approach for the band. [[Moons and Mushrooms]] has a harder rock sound, though Brennare's lyrics continued to lean towards the melancholic and conceptual. \n\nA new album titled ''[[Illwill (album)|Illwill]]'' was released on April 29, 2011. It features an even heavier, darker approach, eschewing the band's typical evocation of mournful themes in favor of bleak and disturbing imagery.\n\nLake of Tears released their first-ever live album on January 31, 2014. The album is titled \"By the Black Sea,\" and includes a full concert with 16 songs recorded earlier this year in Bucharest, Romania. It is also available as DVD/CD set.<ref>[http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/lake-of-tears-to-release-live-album/] {{dead link|date=March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Current line-up ==\n* [[Daniel Brennare]] - Vocals/Guitar (1994\u2013present)\n* [[Mikael Larsson]] - Bass (1994\u2013present)\n* [[Johan Oudhuis]] - Drums (1994\u2013present)\n* [[Fredrik Jordanius]] - Lead guitar (2009\u2013present)\n\n=== Former members ===\n* [[Jonas Eriksson (rhythm guitarist)|Jonas Eriksson]] - Rhythm guitar (1994\u20131997)\n* [[Christian Saarinen]] - Keyboards (1999\u20132000)\n* [[Ulrik Lindblom]] - Guitar (1997\u20131999)\n* [[Magnus Sahlgren]] - Lead guitar (as a guest artist: 1999 / officially: 2004 - 2009)\n\n==Discography==\n===Full length===\n*''[[Greater Art]]'' (1994)\n*''[[Headstones (album)|Headstones]]'' (1995)\n*''[[A Crimson Cosmos]]'' (1997)\n*''[[Forever Autumn (album)|Forever Autumn]]'' (1999)\n*''[[The Neonai]]'' (2002)\n*''[[Black Brick Road]]'' (2004)\n*''[[Moons and Mushrooms]]'' (2007)\n*''[[Illwill (album)|Illwill]]'' (2011)\n\n=== Compilations and singles ===\n*''[[Lady Rosenred]]'' (1997)\n*''[[Sorcerers (album)|Sorcerers]]'' (2002)\n*''[[Greatest Tears Vol. I]]'' (2004)\n*''[[Greatest Tears Vol. II]]'' (2004)\n\n===Live albums===\n*''By the Black Sea'' (2014)\n\n==Sources==\n*[http://www.dockyard1.com Dockyard 1, label]\n*[http://www.dragon-productions.com Dragon Productions, booking agency]\n*[http://www.studiomega.se Home for the BBR recording]\n*[http://www.noiserecords.com Noise Records, old label]\n*[http://www.blackmark.net Black Mark, old label]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.lakeoftears.net Official band web site]\n*[http://www.lakeoftears.org Official fan web site]\n*[http://www.myspace.com/thelakeoftears Lake of Tears on MySpace]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140203125101/http://www.waterytimes.com/index.php?no=8&location=N008C03&txt=N008C03T00 Europe\u2019s Times and Unknown Waters, Ormeny, Francisc-Norbert (30 December 2012).\"The Secrets of the Swedish New Moon\". ]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140203125059/http://www.waterytimes.com/index.php?no=8&location=N008C03&txt=N008C03T01 Europe\u2019s Times and Unknown Waters, Ormeny, Theodora-Eva (30 December 2012).  \"The Aesthetics of Evil Part I\". ]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140203125103/http://www.waterytimes.com/index.php?no=8&location=N008C03&txt=N008C03T02 Europe\u2019s Times and Unknown Waters, Ormeny, Theodora-Eva (30 December 2012).  \"The Aesthetics of Evil Part II\". ]\n\n{{Lake of Tears}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lake Of Tears}}\n[[Category:Swedish heavy metal musical groups]]\n[[Category:Swedish doom metal musical groups]]\n[[Category:Swedish gothic metal musical groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1994]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 2000]]\n[[Category:Musical groups reestablished in 2003]]\n[[Category:Musical quartets]]\n[[Category:1994 establishments in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Black Mark Production artists]]\n[[Category:Noise Records artists]]\n", "name_user": "Paul2520", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixedunrecognized language error(viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lake_of_Tears"}
{"title_page": "Hichem Rostom", "text_new": "{{short description|Tunisian actor}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image =Hichem Rostom 03.JPG\n| caption = Hichem Rostom in 2015.\n| name         = Hichem Rostom\n| native_name       = \u0647\u0634\u0627\u0645 \u0631\u0633\u062a\u0645\n| native_name_lang  = Arabic\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1947|5|26|df=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[La Marsa]], [[Tunisia]]\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| nationality  = Tunisian\n| occupation   = Actor\n| yearsactive  = 1987\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Hichem Rostom''' (born 26 May 1947) is a Tunisian actor of [[Turkish people|Turkish]] origin.<ref>{{cite web|author=Festival Tetouan|title=Hommages 2012: Hichem Rostom , Acteur Tunisien|url=http://www.festivaltetouan.org/page.php?134|accessdate=18 April 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120502142050/http://www.festivaltetouan.org/page.php?134|archivedate=2 May 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He has appeared in 28 films and television shows since 1987. He starred in ''[[Golden Horseshoes]]'', which was screened in the [[Un Certain Regard]] section at the [[1989 Cannes Film Festival|1989 festival]].<ref name=\"cannes-1989.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/260/year/1989.html |title=Festival de Cannes: Golden Horseshoes |accessdate=2 August 2009|work=festival-cannes.com}}</ref> He also directed the Carthage Theatre Festival for two sessions.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sharmfilmfest.com/index.php/festival/jury/132-hichem-rostom|title=Sharm El-Sheikh Arab & European Film Festival|last=admin|first=sharm|access-date=20 July 2017|language=en-gb}}</ref>\n\n==Selected filmography==\n==Cinema==\n==Tunisian feature Films==\n* [[1988]] : ''[[The Golden Clogs]]'' by [[Nouri Bouzid]] : Si Youssef\n* [[1989]] : ''[[Layla, My Reason]]'' by [[Ta\u00efeb Louhichi]] : The Husband of Layla\n* [[1994]] : ''[[The Silence of The Palace]]'' by [[Moufida Tlatli]] : Mr Bacheer\n* [[1997]] : ''[[Essa\u00efda]]'' by [[Mohamed Zran]] : Ameen\n* [[1998]] : ''[[Moon Wedding]]'' by [[Ta\u00efeb Louhichi]]\n* [[1999]] : ''[[Grenadine Naps]]'' by [[Mahmoud Ben Mahmoud]] : Wahid Haydar\n* [[2002]] : ''[[The Magic Box]]'' by [[Ridha B\u00e9hi]) : Mansour\n* [[2002]] : ''[[The Song of The noria]]'' by [[Abdellatif Ben Ammar]) : Ali\n* [[2003]] : ''[[The Murdered Sun]]'' by [[Abdelkrim Bahloul]] : Bramsi\n* [[2004]] : ''[[Nadia and Sarra]]'' by [[Moufida Tlatli]] : Hedy\n* [[2006]] : ''[[The Tv arrives]]'' by [[Moncef Dhouib]] : The Director\n* [[2014]] : ''[[The Child of The Sun]]'' by [[Ta\u00efeb Louhichi]] : Kateb\n* [[2014]] : ''[[Zero !]] by [[Nidhal Chatta]]'' : The Father\n* [[2014]] : ''[[The Last mirage]]'' by [[Nidhal Chatta]] : Dr Oussama Saad\n* [[2015]] : ''[[Dicta Shot]]'' by [[Mokhtar Ladjimi]] : Mr Hazem\n* [[2015]] : ''[[Conflit]]'' by Moncef Barbouch9 : Mokhtar\n* [[2016]] : ''[[Alep's flower]]'' by [[Ridha B\u00e9hi]] : The Father of Mourad\n* [[2016]] : ''[[Woh !]]'' by [[Ismahane Lahmar]] : Hmed\n* [[2016]] : ''[[Whispering Sands]] by [[Nacer Kh\u00e9mir]]\n\n==Longs m\u00e9trages \u00e9trangers==\n* [[1976]] : ''[[Wing or thigh]]'' by [[Claude Zidi]]\n* [[1982]] : ''[[Sandstorm]]''  by [[Mohammed Lakhdar-Hamina]]\n* [[1991]] : ''[[L'amico arabo]] (The Arab Friend) by [[Carmine Fornari]] (it)\n* [[1991]] : ''[[Isabelle Eberhardt]] by [[Ian Pringle]] (en)\n* [[1992]] : ''[[Indiscreet goals]]'' by [[Massimo Mazzuco]] : Manuel The Red\n* [[1993]] : ''[[The Navel of the World]]'' by [[Ariel Zeitoun]] : Costa\n* [[1997]] : ''[[The English Patient]]'' by [[Anthony Minghella]] : Fouad\n* [[1998]] : ''[[Paparazzi]]'' by [[Alain Berberian]] : El Kabouli\n* [[2001]] : ''[[The Desert and the Forest]] (pl) by [[Gavin Hood]] : Mahdi\n* [[2008]] : ''[[The Song of the Brides]] by [[Karin Albou]] : The Father of Raoul\n* [[2008]] : ''[[Whatever Lola Wants]] by [[Nabil Ayouch]] : Nacer\n* [[2011]] : ''[[The Fifth String]] by [[Selma Bergach]] : Amir\n* [[2011]] : ''[[Black Gold]]'' by [[Jean-Jacques Annaud]] : Colonel Nesibi\n\n==Short Films==\n* [[1989]] : ''[[The Trance]]'' by [[Moncef Dhouib]]\n\n==Dubbing==\n* [[2006]] : ''[[Azur and Asmar]]'' by [[Michel Ocelot]] (Dessins Anim\u00e9s)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDB name|0744599|Hichem Rostom}}\n*{{Commons-inline|Category:Hichem Rostom|Hichem Rostom}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rostom, Hichem}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Tunisian people of Turkish descent]]\n[[Category:Tunisian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Tunisian male television actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century Tunisian male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Tunisian male actors]]\n{{Tunisia-actor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Tunisian actor}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image =Hichem Rostom 03.JPG\n| caption = Hichem Rostom in 2015.\n| name         = Hichem Rostom\n| native_name       = \u0647\u0634\u0627\u0645 \u0631\u0633\u062a\u0645\n| native_name_lang  = Arabic\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1947|5|26|df=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[La Marsa]], [[Tunisia]]\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| nationality  = Tunisian\n| occupation   = Actor\n| yearsactive  = 1987\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Hichem Rostom''' (born 26 May 1947) is a Tunisian actor of [[Turkish people|Turkish]] origin.<ref>{{cite web|author=Festival Tetouan|title=Hommages 2012: Hichem Rostom , Acteur Tunisien|url=http://www.festivaltetouan.org/page.php?134|accessdate=18 April 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120502142050/http://www.festivaltetouan.org/page.php?134|archivedate=2 May 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He has appeared in 28 films and television shows since 1987. He starred in ''[[Golden Horseshoes]]'', which was screened in the [[Un Certain Regard]] section at the [[1989 Cannes Film Festival|1989 festival]].<ref name=\"cannes-1989.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/260/year/1989.html |title=Festival de Cannes: Golden Horseshoes |accessdate=2 August 2009|work=festival-cannes.com}}</ref> He also directed the Carthage Theatre Festival for two sessions.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sharmfilmfest.com/index.php/festival/jury/132-hichem-rostom|title=Sharm El-Sheikh Arab & European Film Festival|last=admin|first=sharm|access-date=20 July 2017|language=en-gb}}</ref>\n\n==Selected filmography==\n* ''[[Golden Horseshoes]]'' (1989)\n* ''[[The English Patient (film)|The English Patient]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[Paparazzi (1998 film)|Paparazzi]]'' (1998)\n* ''[[In Desert and Wilderness (2001 film)|In Desert and Wilderness]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[The Magic Box (2002 film)|The Magic Box]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[Colosseum: Rome's Arena of Death]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Whatever Lola Wants (film)|Whatever Lola Wants]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Day of the Falcon]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[The Flower of Aleppo]]'' (2016)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDB name|0744599|Hichem Rostom}}\n*{{Commons-inline|Category:Hichem Rostom|Hichem Rostom}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rostom, Hichem}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Tunisian people of Turkish descent]]\n[[Category:Tunisian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Tunisian male television actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century Tunisian male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Tunisian male actors]]\n{{Tunisia-actor-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Nesrine1984", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSelected filmography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hichem_Rostom"}
